{"date":"2026-01-13T06:18:36.729Z","editing":{},"event":"chat","feedback":{},"folding":[],"history":[{"author_id":"4132ca6e-b0d7-4270-b617-8838d907367a","content":"<span class=\"user-mention\" account-id=google-gemini-3-flash-preview-16k >@Gemini 3 Flash</span> Help me fix my code.\n\n<details open><summary>Context</summary>\n\nI ran a cell in a Jupyter notebook.\n\nI received the following error:\n\n```r\nError in `mutate()`:\nℹ In argument: `Year = str_replace(total_energy$Year, \"[X]\", \"\")`.\nCaused by error:\n! `Year` must be size 3328 or 1, not 0.\nTraceback:\n\n1. mutate(., Total_Energy = as.numeric(str_replace_all(Total_Energy, \n .     \",\", \"\")))\n2. mutate(., Year = str_replace(total_energy$Year, \"[X]\", \"\"))\n3. mutate.data.frame(., Year = str_replace(total_energy$Year, \"[X]\", \n .     \"\"))\n4. mutate_cols(.data, dplyr_quosures(...), by)\n5. withCallingHandlers(for (i in seq_along(dots)) {\n .     poke_error_context(dots, i, mask = mask)\n .     context_poke(\"column\", old_current_column)\n .     new_columns <- mutate_col(dots[[i]], data, mask, new_columns)\n . }, error = dplyr_error_handler(dots = dots, mask = mask, bullets = mutate_bullets, \n .     error_call = error_call, error_class = \"dplyr:::mutate_error\"), \n .     warning = dplyr_warning_handler(state = warnings_state, mask = mask, \n .         error_call = error_call))\n6. mutate_col(dots[[i]], data, mask, new_columns)\n7. mask$eval_all_mutate(quo)\n8. eval()\n9. dplyr_internal_error(\"dplyr:::mutate_incompatible_size\", list(\n .     result_size = 0L, expected_size = 3328L))\n10. abort(class = c(class, \"dplyr:::internal_error\"), dplyr_error_data = data)\n11. signal_abort(cnd, .file)\n12. signalCondition(cnd)\n13. (function (cnd) \n  . {\n  .     local_error_context(dots, i = frame[[i_sym]], mask = mask)\n  .     if (inherits(cnd, \"dplyr:::internal_error\")) {\n  .         parent <- error_cnd(message = bullets(cnd))\n  .     }\n  .     else {\n  .… \"base\", \n  . \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"evaluate\", \"base\", \"base\", \n  . \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"evaluate\", \"base\", \"base\", \n  . \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", \"base\", NA, \"dplyr\", \"dplyr\", \"dplyr\", \n  . \"dplyr\", \"base\", \"dplyr\", NA, \"dplyr\", \"dplyr\", \"rlang\"), scope = c(\"::\", \n  . NA, \"local\", NA, \"::\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \n  . \"local\", \"::\", \"::\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \"local\", \n  . \"local\", \":::\", \"::\", \"::\", \"::\", \"::\", \"::\", \"::\", NA, \"::\", \n  . \"::\", \":::\", \":::\", \"::\", \":::\", NA, \"local\", \":::\", \"::\"), error_frame = c(FALSE, \n  . FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, \n  . FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, \n  . FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, \n  . FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE, FALSE)), row.names = c(NA, \n  . -37L), version = 2L, class = c(\"rlang_trace\", \"rlib_trace\", \"tbl\", \n  . \"data.frame\")), parent = NULL, dplyr_error_data = list(result_size = 0L, \n  .     expected_size = 3328L), rlang = list(inherit = TRUE), call = dplyr_internal_error(\"dplyr:::mutate_incompatible_size\", \n  .     list(result_size = 0L, expected_size = 3328L)), use_cli_format = TRUE), class = c(\"dplyr:::mutate_incompatible_size\", \n  . \"dplyr:::internal_error\", \"rlang_error\", \"error\", \"condition\"\n  . )))\n14. abort(message, class = error_class, parent = parent, call = error_call)\n15. signal_abort(cnd, .file)\n16. signalCondition(cnd)\n```\n\nMy Jupyter notebook using the R (system-wide) kernel contains:\n\n```r\n#PIVOT LONGER to get duplicate states\n#want State in first column, Year in second column, energy consumption in third row\n\ntotal_energy_long <- total_energy %>%\n  pivot_longer(\n    cols = 2:65, #duplicates the state and keeps it in the first column\n    names_to = \"Year\", #variable for headings\n    values_to = \"Total_Energy\" #variables for observations\n  ) %>%\n    \n  mutate(Year = str_replace(total_energy$Year, \"[X]\", \"\")) %>%\n  mutate(Total_Energy = as.numeric(str_replace_all(Total_Energy, \",\", \"\"))) #char -> num and deletes \",\"s in number\n    \ntotal_energy_long\n```\n\n</details>","date":"2026-01-13T06:18:36.729Z"}],"read-4132ca6e-b0d7-4270-b617-8838d907367a":2,"sender_id":"4132ca6e-b0d7-4270-b617-8838d907367a"}
{"date":"2026-01-13T06:18:36.731Z","editing":{},"event":"chat","generating":false,"history":[{"author_id":"google-gemini-3-flash-preview-16k","content":"The error occurs because you are using `total_energy$Year` inside the `mutate()` function. Since you are using a pipe (`%>%`), you should refer to the column name directly. \n\nAdditionally, if `total_energy` is the original \"wide\" dataframe, it likely does not have a column named `Year` yet (those are your column headers), causing `total_energy$Year` to return `NULL` (size 0).\n\n### Fixed Code:\n\n```r\ntotal_energy_long <- total_energy %>%\n  pivot_longer(\n    cols = 2:65, \n    names_to = \"Year\", \n    values_to = \"Total_Energy\"\n  ) %>%\n  mutate(\n    # Remove 'total_energy$' to reference the column created by pivot_longer\n    Year = str_replace(Year, \"X\", \"\"), \n    Total_Energy = as.numeric(str_replace_all(Total_Energy, \",\", \"\"))\n  )\n    \ntotal_energy_long\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n1.  Changed `str_replace(total_energy$Year, ...)` to `str_replace(Year, ...)`.\n2.  Simplified the regex `\"[X]\"` to `\"X\"` (unless you specifically need the brackets).\n3.  Combined the two `mutate()` calls into one for efficiency.","date":"2026-01-13T06:18:43.140Z"}],"reply_to":"2026-01-13T06:18:36.729Z","sender_id":"google-gemini-3-flash-preview-16k"}